Module 86 – Timeline → Brief: Turning Chronology into Argument ⏳➡️📄
⚖️ Core Message
A good appellate section is a cleaned timeline with standards. Move from chronology to headings that map to relief.

📖 Lesson Content
• Three Columns — Date • Event • Cite (ECF/Exhibit/Hash).
• Grouping — Cluster events by issue (service, findings, suppression).
• Bridge — For each cluster, add a rule/standard and the ask.
• Template — Use the timeline as a FRE 1006 exhibit and as the brief's backbone.
• Pin‑Cites — Every sentence gets a cite or moves to argument.
📝 Assignment
Draft a 1‑page timeline and convert it into three issue headings with standards and asks.

✅ Model Answer (Template)
HEADING: Denial without Findings (Abuse of Discretion). Timeline ¶¶ 8–12; ask: vacatur & remand for findings.

💡 Reflection
Chronology persuades when it’s tied to the standard and the remedy.

🎨 Visual Pairing
An arrow flowing from 'Timeline' boxes into 'Brief' headings.



